[
  {
    "type": "h1",
    "content": "Basics"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 1"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "For the function $ f(x) = \\frac {x} {2x - 1} $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "a) Determine its derivative $ f'(x) $."
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "b) Determine the equation of the tangent line to $ f(x) $ at $ x = 1 $."
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "a) To find the derivative, we will use the first principles formula:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {f(x + h) - f(x)} {h} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {\\frac {x + h} {2(x + h) - 1} - \\frac {x} {2x - 1}} {h} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {\\frac {x + h} {2x + 2h - 1} - \\frac {x} {2x - 1}} {h} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {\\frac {(x + h)(2x - 1)} {(2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)} - \\frac {x(2x + 2h - 1)} {(2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)}} {h} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {(x + h)(2x - 1) - x(2x + 2h - 1)} {h(2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {2x^2 - x + 2hx - h - 2x^2 - 2xh + x} {h(2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {\\cancel{2x^2} \\cancel{-x} \\cancel{+2hx} - h \\cancel{-2x^2} \\cancel{-2xh} + \\cancel{x}} {h(2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {-h} {h(2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {-\\cancel{h}} { \\cancel{h} (2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\ ^{\\lim}_{h \\to 0} \\frac {-1} {(2x - 1)(2x + 2h - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\frac {-1} {(2x - 1)(2x + 2(0) - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\frac {-1} {(2x - 1)(2x - 1)} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\frac {-1} {(2x - 1)^2} $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "b) To find the tangent equation at for $ f(x) $ at $ x = 1 $, we need $ f(1) $ and $ f'(1) $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f(1) = \\frac {1} {2(1) - 1} = \\frac {1} {2 - 1} = 1 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(1) = \\frac {-1} {(2(1) - 1)^2} = \\frac {1} {1^2} = 1 = m_T $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Now, we just need to plug in the values into the following equation of a tangent line:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y - y_1 = m_T(x - x_1) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y - (1) = (1)(x - (1)) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y = (x - 1) + 1 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 2"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "The tangent to the graph of $ f(x) = \\frac {1} {(x - 1)^2} $ at the point $ (2, \\ 1) $ forms a triangle with and $x$ and $y$ axis. Determine the area of that triangle."
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "If we get the equation of the tangent line at $ (2, \\ 1) $, we can get the height of the triangle when $ x = 0 $ (intersects $y$-axis) and the width of the triangle when $ y = 0 $ (intersects $x$-axis)."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "First let's work on finding the derivative $ f'(x) $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f(x) = \\frac {1} {(x - 1)^2} = (x - 1)^{-2} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = -2(x - 1)^{-3} (1) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\frac {-2} {(x - 1)^3} $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Now let's find the values for needed for the tangent line:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(2) = \\frac {-2} {((2) - 1)^3} = \\frac {-2} {1^3} = -2 = m_T $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\, \\, y - y_1 = m_T(x - x_1) $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y - (1) = (-2)(x - (2)) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\, \\, y = -2x + 4 - 1 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\, \\, y = -2x + 3 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "So, the dimensions of the triangle are:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y = -2(0) + 5 = 5 \\ \\Rightarrow \\ \\text{Height} = 5 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 0 = -2x + 5 \\ \\Rightarrow \\ x = \\frac {5} {2} \\ \\Rightarrow \\ \\text{Width} = \\frac {5} {2} $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Finally, the area of the triangle is:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\text {Area} = \\frac { \\text {height} \\times \\text {width} } {2} = \\frac {5 \\times \\frac {5} {2}} {2} = 6.25 =$"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\therefore $ The area of the triangle is $ 6.25 $ units squared."
  },
  {
    "type": "h1",
    "content": "Derivative Rules"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 3"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "If $ h(x) = f[g(x)] + f(x)g(x) $, $ f(2) = 4 $, $ g(2) = -1 $, $ f'(-1) = 3 $, $ f'(2) = 0 $ and $ g'(2) = 2 $, then find $ h'(2) $."
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ h'(x) = f'(g(x))g'(x) + f'(x)g(x) + f(x)g'(x) $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ h'(2) = f'(g(2))g'(2) + f'(2)g(2) + f(2)g'(2) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ h'(2) = f'(-1)(2) + (0)(-1) + (4)(2) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ h'(2) = (3)(2) + (4)(2) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ h'(2) = 6 + 8 = 14 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h1",
    "content": "Derivative Of Special Function"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 4"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Find the derivative of $ \\cot x $ (remember,  $ \\cot x = \\frac {\\cos x} {\\sin x} $)."
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "We can solve this derivative by using the quotient rule:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\frac {d} {dx} [ \\cot x ] = \\frac {(\\sin x) \\frac {d} {dx} (\\cos x) - (\\cos x) \\frac {d} {dx} (\\sin x) } {(\\sin x)^2} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\ \\ \\ \\ = \\frac {(\\sin x)(-\\sin x) - (\\cos x)(\\cos x) } {\\sin^2 x} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\ \\ \\ \\ = \\frac {-\\sin^2 x - \\cos^2 x } {\\sin^2 x} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\ \\ \\ \\ = \\frac {-(\\sin^2 x + \\cos^2 x) } {\\sin^2 x} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\ \\ \\ \\ = - \\frac {1} {\\sin^2 x} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\ \\ \\ \\ = - \\csc^2 x $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\therefore \\frac {d} {dx} [ \\cot x ] = - \\csc^2 x $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 5"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Find the derivatives of the following functions:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "a) $ y = \\log_{5} (3x^2 - \\pi x) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "b) $ y = e^{\\ln \\sqrt{\\sin 2x} } $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "c) $ y = e^{x^2+5x} \\ln (3x+1) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "a) Differentiating this function requires the use of the chain rule, since it takes the form $ f(g(x)) $. The outer function is $ f(x) = \\log_{5} x $ and the inner function is $ g(x) = 3x^2 - \\pi x $."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "First, find the derivatives of both functions:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "The derivative of the outer function is $ f'(x) = (\\frac {1} {x}) (\\frac {1} {ln5}) $."
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "The derivative of the inner function is $ g'(x) = 6x \\ - \\ \\pi $."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Now, substitute $ g(x) $ for $x$ the derivative of the outer function, and multiply everything by $ g'(x) $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y' = f'(g(x)) \\ g'(x) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad = (\\frac {1} {3x^2 \\ - \\ \\pi x})(\\frac {1} {\\ln 5})(6x \\ - \\ \\pi) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad = \\frac {6x \\ - \\ \\pi} {(3x^2 \\ - \\ \\pi x)( \\ln 5)}$"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\therefore y' = \\frac {6x \\ - \\ \\pi} {(3x^2 \\ - \\ \\pi x)( \\ln 5)}$"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "b) First, simplify the function to make it a bit easier: "
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y = e^{\\ln \\sqrt{\\sin 2x} } = e^{\\frac{1}{2} \\ln (\\sin 2x) } $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Then, notice that we have three major functions \"chained\" in the form $ f(g(h(x))) $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "ul",
    "contents": [
      {
        "type": "p",
        "content": "$ f(x) = e^x $"
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "content": "$ g(x) = \\frac{1}{2} \\ln x $"
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "content": "$ h(x) = \\sin 2x $"
      }
    ]
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Find their derivatives:"
  },
  {
    "type": "ul",
    "contents": [
      {
        "type": "p",
        "content": "$ f'(x) = e^x $"
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "content": "$ g'(x) = \\frac{1}{2x} $"
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "content": "$ h'(x) = 2 \\cos 2x $"
      }
    ]
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Finally, apply the chain rule to get the derivative of the entire function:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y' = f'(g(h(x))) \\ g'(h(x)) \\ h'(x) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad = (e^{\\frac{1}{2} \\ln (\\sin 2x) })(\\frac{1}{2\\sin 2x})(2\\cos 2x) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad = (e^{\\frac{1}{2} \\ln (\\sin 2x) })(\\cot 2x)$"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\therefore y' = (e^{\\frac{1}{2} \\ln (\\sin 2x) })(\\cot 2x)$"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "This question was quite tough, however, with enough practice you can eventually to this all in your head!"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "c) This function requires the use of product rule and chain rule."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "First find the two functions being multiplied by each other:"
  },
  {
    "type": "ul",
    "contents": [
      {
        "type": "p",
        "content": "$ f(x) = e^{x^2+5x} $"
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "content": "$ g(x) = \\ln (3x+1) $"
      }
    ]
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Then, find their derivatives using chain rule:"
  },
  {
    "type": "ul",
    "contents": [
      {
        "type": "p",
        "content": "$ f'(x) = e^{x^2+5x} (2x+5) $"
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "content": "$ g'(x) = \\frac {1} {3x+1} (3) $"
      }
    ]
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Finally, use product rule to find the derivative of the entire function:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y' = f(x)g'(x) + f'(x)g(x) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad = (e^{x^2+5x})(\\frac {1} {3x+1})(3) + (e^{x^2+5x})(2x+5)(\\ln (3x+1)) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad = \\frac {3e^{x^2+5x}} {3x+1} + (2x+5) e^{x^2+5x} \\ln (3x+1) $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\therefore y' = \\frac {3e^{x^2+5x}} {3x+1} + (2x+5) e^{x^2+5x} \\ln (3x+1) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h1",
    "content": "Derivative Properties"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 6"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Suppose that $ f(x) = ax^3 + bx^2 + cx $ has a local maximum at $ (-1, 7) $ and an inflection point at $ x = \\frac {1} {2} $, find the values of $a$, $b$, $c$."
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Let's begin by listing the function and its first and second derivatives:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f(x) = ax^3 + bx^2 + cx $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = 3ax^2 + 2bx + c $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f''(x) = 6ax + 2b $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "The question gives us the local maximum as a point $ (-1, 7) $ on the graph. We can use this to create one equation:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f(-1) = 7$"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ 7 = a(-1)^3 + b(-1)^2 + c(-1) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ 7 = -a + b - c $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ c = -a + b - 7 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "There is also a local maximum at point at $ x = -1 $, meaning $ f'(-1) = 0 $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(-1) = 0 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\, 0 = 3a(-1)^2 + 2b(-1) + c $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\, 0 = 3a - 2b + c $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "There is an inflection point at $ x = \\frac {1} {2} $, meaning $ f''(\\frac {1} {2}) = 0 $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f''(\\frac {1} {2}) = 0 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\ \\ \\ \\, 0 = 6a(\\frac {1} {2}) + 2b $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\ \\ \\ \\, 0 = 3a + 2b $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\ \\ \\, \\, \\, b = - \\frac {3} {2} a $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Now we just plug in the equations into each others so that we obtain the values for $a$, $b$ and $c$:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 0 = 3a - 2b + c $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 0 = 2a - b - 7 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\, b = 2a - 7 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\ \\ \\, \\,  b = - \\frac {3} {2} a $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ (2a - 7) = - \\frac {3} {2} a $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\, \\, 4a - 14 = - 3a $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\, \\, 7a = 14 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad a = 2 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ b = - \\frac {3} {2} a $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ b = - \\frac {3} {2} (2) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ b = -3 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ c = b - a - 7 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ c = (-3) - (2) - 7 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ c = -12 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\therefore a = 2 $, $ b = -3 $ and $ c = -12 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 7"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "The following graph shows that there are two tangent lines to both of the parabolas $ f(x) = -x^2 $ and $ g(x) = 4 + x^2 $. Find the coordinates of the four points at which the tangents touch the parabolas."
  },
  {
    "type": "image",
    "url": "/images/lectures/derivative-properties-8.png"
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Let's begin by calculating the derivatives of the functions:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f(x) = -x^2 \\ \\Rightarrow \\ f'(x) = -2x $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ g(x) = 4 + x^2 \\ \\Rightarrow \\ g'(x) = 2x $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Say that the $x$ coordinate of the point we are looking for is $a$."
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Note that the slope at $ x = a $ is the same as the slope at $ x = -a $ on different parabolas."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "For the tangent that goes from the top left to the bottom right, we can derive its tangent equation from both $ f(x) $ and $ g(x) $, then solve for $a$."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "For $ f(x) $, the tangent intersects at $ x = a $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ m_{T_a} = f'(a) = -2(a) = -2a $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f(a) = -(a)^2 = -a^2 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y_T - y_1 = m_{T_a}(x - x_1) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y_T - (-a^2) = (-2a)(x - (a)) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y_T = -2ax + a^2 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "For $ g(x) $, the tangent intersects at $ x = -a $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ m_{T_b} = g'(a) = 2(-a) = -2a $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ g(a) = 4 + (a)^2 = 4 + a^2 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y_T - y_1 = m_{T_b}(x - x_1) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y_T - (4 + a^2) = (-2a)(x - (-a)) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ y_T = -2ax - a^2 + 4 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Now, plug the equations into each other and solve for $a$:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ -2ax + a^2 = -2ax - a^2 + 4 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$  2a^2 = 4 \\ \\Rightarrow \\ a = \\pm \\sqrt {2} $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Finally, find the points on both functions at $ a = \\pm \\sqrt {2} $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ (+ \\sqrt{2}, \\ f(+ \\sqrt{2})) = (+ \\sqrt{2}, \\ -2) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ (+ \\sqrt{2}, \\ g(+ \\sqrt{2})) = (+ \\sqrt{2}, \\ 6) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ (- \\sqrt{2}, \\ f(- \\sqrt{2})) = (- \\sqrt{2}, \\ -2) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ (- \\sqrt{2}, \\ g(- \\sqrt{2})) = (- \\sqrt{2}, \\ 6) $"
  },
  {
