    "content": "Optimization"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 8"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "A garden is in the shape of a semi-circle with a radius of $ 2m $. The grey region is to be covered with landscaping rocks at a cost of $ \\$ 50/m^2 $, while the green triangular region is to be covered with flowers at a cost of $ \\$ 25/m^2 $."
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "a) Find a function for the cost of the garden as a function of the angle $ \\theta $."
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "b) Determine angle $ \\theta $ to minimize the cost of the garden. How much will the orcks and flowers for the garden cost?"
  },
  {
    "type": "video",
    "url": "/videos/lectures/optimization-4.mp4"
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "a) We can model the cost function as:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ C = 50(A_{ \\text{rocks} }) + 25(A_{ \\text{flowers} }) $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "The area of the flowers triangle can be calculated as follows:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\text {base} = 2 \\times 2 = 4 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\sin \\theta = \\frac { \\text{height} } {2} \\ \\Rightarrow \\ \\text{height} = 2 \\sin \\theta $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ A_{flowers} = \\frac {1} {2} \\cdot \\text{base} \\cdot \\text{height} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\ \\ = \\frac {1} {2} \\cdot (4) \\cdot (2 \\sin \\theta) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\ \\ = 4 \\sin \\theta $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "The area of the landscaping area can be calculated as follows:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ A_{ \\text{semi-circle} } = \\frac {1} {2} \\pi r^2 = \\frac {1} {2} \\pi (2)^2 = 2 \\pi $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ A_{ \\text{rocks} } = A_{ \\text{semi-circle} } - A_{ \\text{flowers} } $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\ \\, = (2 \\pi) - (4 \\sin \\theta) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\ \\, = 2 \\pi - 4 \\sin \\theta $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Now, let's form the final cost equation as a function of $ \\theta $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ C(\\theta) = 50(A_{ \\text{rocks} }) + 25(A_{ \\text{flowers} }) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\, = 50(2 \\pi - 4 \\sin \\theta) + 25(4 \\sin \\theta) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\, = 100 \\pi - 200 \\sin \\theta + 100 \\sin \\theta $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\, = 100 \\pi - 100 \\sin \\theta $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\therefore $ The equation for the cost of the garden is $ C(\\theta) = 100 \\pi - 100 \\sin \\theta $."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "b) We can determine the angle that will minimize the cost of the garden by looking at the derivative of the cost function:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ C(\\theta) = 100 \\pi - 100 \\sin \\theta $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ C'(\\theta) = -100 \\cos \\theta $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Now we need to find the critical points of $ C'(\\theta) $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ C'(\\theta) = 0 $ when $ \\theta = \\frac {\\pi} {2} $ or $ \\cancel{ \\frac {3 \\pi} {2} } \\ $ (invalid b/c $ 0 < \\theta < \\pi $)"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Now we have to confirm that this is a minimum:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "when $ \\theta < \\frac {\\pi} {2} $, $ C'(\\theta) < 0 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "when $ \\theta > \\frac {\\pi} {2} $, $ C'(\\theta) > 0 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "So, the minimum cost of the garden occurs at an angle of $ \\theta = \\frac {\\pi} {2} $."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "The actual cost of the garden at its minimum is:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ C(\\frac {\\pi} {2}) = 100 \\pi - 100 \\sin (\\frac {\\pi} {2}) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\, \\, = 100 \\pi - 100(1) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\ \\, \\, \\approx 214 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\therefore $ The minimum price of the garden is approximately 214 dollars and occurs at an angle of $ \\theta = \\frac {\\pi} {2} $."
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 9"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "A fuel tank is being designed to contain $ 200m^3 $ of gasoline. The design of the tank calls of a cylindrical part in the middle with a hemisphere (semi-sphere) at each end to make a \"pill\" shape. If the hemispheres are twice as expensive per unit area as the cylindrical wall, then find the radius and height of the cylindrical part so that the cost of manufacturing the tank will be minimal."
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "Answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "First of all, we need to know the formulas for the volume of a semi-sphere and a cylinder:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 2(V_{ \\text{semi-sphere} }) = V_{ \\text{sphere} } = \\frac {4} {3} \\pi r^3 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ V_{ \\text{cylinder} } = \\pi r^2 h $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "If we want to optimize this problem, we need the cost of the fuel tank in terms of one variable. In this case we have two."
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Luckily, we can get get $h$ in terms of $r$ by using the fact that the fuel tank must have a volume of $ 200m^3 $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\ \\, \\, 200 = \\frac {4} {3} \\pi r^3 + \\pi r^2 h $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\pi r^2 h = 200 - \\frac {4} {3} \\pi r^3 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\ \\, \\, h = \\frac {200 - \\frac {4} {3} \\pi r^3} {\\pi r^2} $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Now we can get the areas of the semi-spheres and the outer part of the cylinder in terms of $r$ only:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 2(A_{ \\text{semi-sphere} }) = A_{ \\text{sphere} } = 4 \\pi r^2 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ A_{ \\text{outer cylinder} } = 2 \\pi rh $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\, \\, = 2 \\pi r (\\frac {200 - \\frac {4} {3} \\pi r^3} {\\pi r^2}) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\, \\, = 2 \\cancel{\\pi r} (\\frac {200 - \\frac {4} {3} \\pi r^3} {\\cancel {\\pi} r^{\\cancel {2}^1}}) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\, \\, = \\frac {400 - \\frac {8} {3} \\pi r^3} {r} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\, \\, = 400r^{-1} - \\frac {8} {3} \\pi r^2 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Now we need to maximize the cost. Not the area! Many people get that wrong."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Since the cost for the semi-sphere material is twice as expensive, we will multiply it my two:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\text {Cost} (r) = 2(A_{ \\text{sphere} }) + A_{ \\text{outer cylinder} } $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\ \\, \\, = 2(4 \\pi r^2) + 400r^{-1} - \\frac {8} {3} \\pi r^2 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\ \\, \\, = 8 \\pi r^2 + 400r^{-1} - \\frac {8} {3} \\pi r^2 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\ \\, \\, = \\frac {16} {3} \\pi r^2 + 400r^{-1} $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "The derivative of the cost function is:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\text {Cost}'(r) = (2)(\\frac {16} {3} \\pi r) + (-1)(400r^{-2}) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\ \\ \\, \\, = \\frac {32} {3} \\pi r - 400r^{-2} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\ \\ \\, \\, = \\frac {32} {3} \\pi r \\frac {r^2} {r^2} - \\frac {400} {r^2} \\times \\frac {3} {3} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\ \\ \\, \\, = \\frac {32 \\pi r^3 - 1200} {3r^2} $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "The critical points are:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\cancel{r = 0} $ because $ r > 0 $, and,"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ 32 \\pi r^3 - 1200 = 0 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\ \\ \\ \\, r^3 = \\frac {75} {2 \\pi} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\, \\, r = \\sqrt [3] {\\frac {75} {2 \\pi}} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\, \\, r \\approx 2.285 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "When $ 0 < r < 2.285 $, $ \\text {Cost}'(r) < 0 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "When $ r > 2.285 $, $ \\text {Cost}'(r) > 0 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "So, there is a minimum at $ r \\approx 2.285 $."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Finally, the height of the cylinder is:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ h = \\frac {200 - \\frac {4} {3} \\pi (2.285)^3} {\\pi (2.285)^2} \\approx 9.146 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ \\therefore $ A radius of approximately $ 2.285m $ and a height of $ 9.146m $ would result in the least expensive cost to make the fuel tank."
  },
  {
    "type": "h1",
    "content": "Curve Sketching"
  },
  {
    "type": "h2",
    "content": "Question 10"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Sketch the graph of $ f(x) = (\\ln x)^2 + 1 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "h3",
    "content": "answer"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "Before starting, let's find $ f'(x) $ and $ f''(x) $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = 2(\\ln x)(\\frac {1} {x}) = \\frac {2 \\ln x} {x} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f''(x) = \\frac {2(\\frac {1}{x})(x) - (2 \\ln x)(1)} {x^2} = \\frac {2 - 2 \\ln x} {x^2} $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "1) Find the discontinuities and their behaviours:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ (\\ln x)^2 $ is undefined when $ x \\le 0 \\Rightarrow \\ x = 0 $ is a vertical asumptote"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 0^+} (\\ln x)^2 + 1 = (\\ln 0^+)^2 + 1 = + \\infty + 1 = + \\infty $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to 0^-} (\\ln x)^2 + 1 \\ $ does not exist"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "For the horizontal asymptotes:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to + \\infty} (\\ln x)^2 + 1 = (+ \\infty)^2 + 1 = + \\infty \\Rightarrow \\ $ No horizontal asymptote"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ ^{\\lim}_{x \\to - \\infty} (\\ln x)^2 + 1 \\ $ does not exist"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "2) Now we need to determine the critical points:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = \\frac {2 \\ln x} {x} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f'(x) = 0 \\ $ when $ 2 \\ln x = 0 \\Rightarrow \\ $ There is a critical point at $ x = 1 $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f(1) = (\\ln (1))^2 + 1 = 0 + 1 = 1 \\Rightarrow \\ $ The critical point is at $ (1, 1) $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "There is also a critical point at $ x = 0 $, since it is undefined for $ f'(x) $."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "3), 4) Find the intervals of increase/decrease/neither and determine if the critical point is a minimum/maximum/neither:"
  },
  {
    "type": "table",
    "gridTemplateColumns": "repeat(3, 1fr)",
    "rows": [
      {
        "header": true,
        "cells": [
          {
            "type": "p",
            "content": "$ x < 0 $"
          },
          {
            "type": "p",
            "content": "$ 0 < x < 1 $"
          },
          {
            "type": "p",
            "content": "$ x > 1 $"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "cells": [
          {
            "type": "p",
            "content": "$ f'(x) $ DNE"
          },
          {
            "type": "p",
            "content": "$ f'(x) < 0 $"
          },
          {
            "type": "p",
            "content": "$ f'(x) > 0 $"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "So, $ f(x) $ is decreasing when $ 0 < x < 1 $ and increasing when $ x > 1 $."
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "There is also a local minimum at $ (1, 1) $ since the function goes from decreasing to increasing."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "5), 6) Now we must find the points of inflection and the intervals of concavity for $ f(x) $:"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$f''(x) = \\frac {2 - 2 \\ln x} {x^2} $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f''(x) = 0 $ when $ 2 - 2 \\ln x = 0 \\Rightarrow \\ln x = 1 \\Rightarrow x = e $"
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "$ f''(x) $ is also undefined at $ x = 0 $"
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "table",
    "gridTemplateColumns": "repeat(3, 1fr)",
    "rows": [
      {
        "header": true,
        "cells": [
          {
            "type": "p",
            "content": "$ x < 0 $"
          },
          {
            "type": "p",
            "content": "$ 0 < x < e $"
          },
          {
            "type": "p",
            "content": "$ x > e $"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "cells": [
          {
            "type": "p",
            "content": "$ f''(x) $ DNE"
          },
          {
            "type": "p",
            "content": "$ f''(x) > 0 $"
          },
          {
            "type": "p",
            "content": "$ f''(x) < 0 $"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "So, $ f(x) $ is concave up when $ 0 < x < e $ and concave down when $ x > e $."
  },
  { "type": "br" },
  {
    "type": "p",
    "content": "7) Now we can draw the graph:"
  },
